0. Prerequisites/Installations

We have some installations to complete first. This should take no time at all.

0.1 Install {rdflib} + dependencies

Ubuntu/Debian

For Ubuntu/Debian, open the terminal and install librdf0-dev:

sudo apt-get install librdf0-de

so that {rdflib} can rely on {redland} - an R interface to the Redland RDF C library.

Then: install.packages('rdflib') from your R session. Also, please install.packages('jsonld') - the {jsonld} package that parses JSON-LD, a semantic web flavour of JSON (JSON-LD == JSON for Linked Data).

Windows

Windows users should be able to install everything by just doing install.packages(). When installing {rdflib} accept installing from source when prompted.

[OPTIONAL] 0.2 Install {rrdf} + dependencies

Following the instructions from https://github.com/egonw/rrdf

You will need {devtools} if not already installed (and if not… install.packages('devtools')), and {rJava} (install.packages('rJava')).

Then:

devtools::install_github("egonw/rrdf", subdir="rrdflibs") devtools::install_github("egonw/rrdf", subdir="rrdf", build_vignettes = FALSE)

This will install the {rrdf} package to handle RDF + {rrdflibs}: the Apache Jena libraries. Long story shor: Apache Jena is “… a free and open source Java framework for building Semantic Web and Linked Data applications”, while {rrdf} wraps R around it. We will rely more on the {rdflib} package (instaled in section 0.1) in this Notebook ({rrdf} is not on CRAN anymore, and I have no idea if it is maintained anymore). However, Apache Jena itself is very popular.

0.3 {jsonlite} to parse JSON and {SPARQL}

install.packages('jsonlite') install.packages('SPARQL')

0.4 Wikidata and Wikipedia related packages

install.packages('WikidataR') install.packages('WikidataQueryServiceR') install.packages('WikipediR')

0.5 {visNetwork} for graph visualizations and {leaflet} for maps

Install {visNetwork} for graph visualizations using vis.js javascript library:

install.packages('visNetwork') install.packages('leaflet')

1. Transform a dataframe into an RDF adherent graph representation and back

The roadmap. We want to start from an R data.frame class, a form of data representation well-known to Data Scientists, transform it to a graph in compliance with the RDF (Resource Description Framework) Semantic Web standard, store in an in-memory triplestore with {rdflib}, and query it with SPARQL query language for RDF.

Let’s use the well-known mtcars dataset.

1.1 Crash mtcars: a dataframe goes into a triplestore

data(mtcars)
head(mtcars, 5)

We will begin by using tidyr::pivot_longer() - a new approach to a short-to-long data transform in {tidyr} - to produce a set of Subject-Predicate-Object triples from mtcars:

car_triples <- 
  mtcars %>% 
  rownames_to_column("model") %>% 
  pivot_longer(-model, 
               names_to = "attribute", 
               values_to = "value")
head(car_triples, 10)

Still I don’t want my Subject-Predicate-Object triples to go under Model, attribute, and value, and moreover I do not want the data in the model column to play the Subject role. I want to have one concept, a sort of an ID, identified by an URI to represent the “things” here, and then model will be just another predicate to describe things.

# - produce URIs
car_triples_0 <- 
  mtcars %>%
  rownames_to_column("model") %>% 
  select("model") %>% 
  rownames_to_column("subject")
car_triples_0$subject <- paste0("http://e-rum2020_example.com/mtcars#", 
                                car_triples_0$model)
head(car_triples_0, 10)

Now we have an URI for each model. Next, add the predicate model to the representation, and rename to Subject-Predicate-Object:

# - Subject - Predicate - Object
car_triples_0$predicate <- "model"
colnames(car_triples_0) <- c("subject", "object", "predicate")
car_triples_0 <- car_triples_0[, c("subject", "predicate", "object")]
head(car_triples_0, 10)

Finally, let’s left_join the car_triples_0 with the URIs to car_triples, introduce Subject-Predicate-Object column names, and rbind() the the car_triples set of triples with car_triples_0 where the values for the model predicate is stored.

# - join URIs to car_triples
car_triples <- 
  car_triples %>%  
  left_join(select(car_triples_0, -predicate), 
            by = c("model" = "object")) %>% 
  select(-model)
colnames(car_triples) <- c("predicate", "object", "subject")
car_triples <- car_triples[, c("subject", "predicate", "object")]  

# - put it together:
car_triples <- rbind(car_triples, car_triples_0)
rm(car_triples_0)
head(car_triples, 10)

We need URIs for the predicates too:

# - Predicate URIs
car_triples$predicate <- paste0("http://e-rum2020_example.com/mtcars#",
                                car_triples$predicate)
head(car_triples, 10)

In the object column we now find only values. We want to add the RDF compliant datatype descriptors to those, and RDF borrows its data types from the XML Schema. I will parse the values in the object column with regex to identify the types. Note. This feels a bit uncomfortable, I know: sometimes R can parse a set of plain values and determine their XML Schema datatype for you, as we will see later.

# - Datatypes defined in XML Schema 1.1 Part 2: Datatypes [XMLSCHEMA11-2]: 
# - https://www.w3.org/TR/rdf11-concepts/#section-Datatypes
# - XML Schema Datatypes are URIs of the form http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#xxx
# - xxx is the name of a datatype
car_triples$object <- sapply(car_triples$object,
                             function(x) {
                               if (grepl('^[[:digit:]]+$', x)) {
                                 return(paste0('"', x, '"', '^^', '<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#integer>'))
                               } else if (grepl('^[[:digit:]]+\\.[[:digit:]]+$|^\\.[[:digit:]]+$', x)) {
                                 return(paste0('"', x, '"', '^^', '<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#double>'))
                               } else if (grepl('[[:alpha:]]', x)) {
                                 return(paste0('"', x, '"', '^^', '<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string>'))
                               }
                             })
head(
  data.frame(
    object = car_triples$object, 
    stringsAsFactors = F), 
  10)

Let’s simplify the representation by introducing prefixes: xsd for http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema and erum2020mtcars for http://e-rum2020_example.com/mtcars: car_triples_prefixed.

# - use xsd prefix to simplify object
car_triples_prefixed <- car_triples  
car_triples_prefixed$object <- gsub("http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#",
                                    "xsd:",
                                    car_triples_prefixed$object)
# - use prefix mtcars to simplify predicate
car_triples_prefixed$predicate <- gsub("http://e-rum2020_example.com/mtcars#",
                                       "erum2020mtcars:",
                                       car_triples_prefixed$predicate)
# - use prefix mtcars to simplify subject
car_triples_prefixed$subject <- gsub("http://e-rum2020_example.com/mtcars#",
                                     "erum2020mtcars:",
                                     car_triples_prefixed$subject)
head(car_triples_prefixed, 10)

1.2 Visualize the mtcars triplestore as a graph

Let’s take a look at a subset of the mtcars dataset, represented as a set of triple. We will downsample car_triples in order to obtain a managable visualization:

# - visualize mtcars graph
# - nodes
nodes <- unique(c(car_triples_prefixed$subject, car_triples_prefixed$object))
graph_nodes <- data.frame(id = 1:length(nodes),
                          label = nodes,
                          stringsAsFactors = F)
graph_nodes$color <- ifelse(grepl("mtcars:", graph_nodes$label), "lightblue", "lightgreen")
graph_nodes$size <- ifelse(grepl("mtcars:", graph_nodes$label), 15, 5)
graph_nodes$shadow <- T
graph_nodes$font.face <- "sans-serif"
graph_nodes$font.size <- 10
# - edges
from <- graph_nodes$id[match(car_triples_prefixed$subject, graph_nodes$label)]
to <- graph_nodes$id[match(car_triples_prefixed$object, graph_nodes$label)]
graph_edges <- data.frame(from = from, 
                          to = to,
                          label = car_triples_prefixed$predicate,
                          stringsAsFactors = F)
graph_edges$color <- "gray"
graph_edges$smooth <- T
graph_edges$width <- .25
graph_edges$font.size <- 8
# - downsample graph for visualization
searchQuery <- "Merc"
wSearch <- graph_nodes$id[which(grepl(searchQuery, graph_nodes$label))]
graph_edges_0 <- graph_edges %>% 
  filter(from %in% wSearch)
graph_nodes_0 <- graph_nodes %>% 
  filter((id %in% graph_edges_0$from) | (id %in% graph_edges_0$to))
# - visualize
visNetwork(nodes = graph_nodes_0,
           edges = graph_edges_0, 
           main = list(text = "MTCARS example",
                       style = "font-family:sans-serif;font-size:15px;text-align:center;"))

At this point, mtcars has a form of a triplestore, but it is still an R data.frame. It is good for nothing.

2. RDF representation and serializations w. {rdflib}

Let’s get back to mtcars represented by car_triples. We will now turn car_triples into an in-memory triplestore from {rdflib}. We first initialize an rdf object in {rdflib}:

# - init an rdf object
triplestore <- rdf()

2.1 Populating {rdflib} triplestores

Now we use rdf_add() to add subjects, objects, and predicates - the triples - to our triplestore triplestore:

prefix_mtcars <- "http://e-rum2020_example.com/mtcars#"
# - add one triple
triplestore %>% 
  rdf_add(subject = paste0(prefix_mtcars, car_triples$subject[1]), 
          predicate = paste0(prefix_mtcars, car_triples$predicate[1]), 
          object = car_triples$object[1])
print(triplestore)

# - init an rdf object

3. From RDF to data.frame: reconstruct mtcars with SPARQL

Finally, let’s start reconstructing the mtcars data.frame from its RDF representation in the triplestore. We will use SPARQL. SPARQL stands for: SPARQL Protocol and RDF Query Language, and it is a query language for RDF.

3.1 Find a particular car from mtcars

The following query will: - try to bind to the variable ?subject all the the URIs that have the value of 2.2 on the wt predicate; - try to bind to the variable ?model the value of the model predicate corresponding to each selected ?subject.

# - SPARQL: query triplestore
# - car with wt == 2.2: id, model
sparqlQuery <-
  'PREFIX mtcars:<http://e-rum2020_example.com/mtcars#> 
   PREFIX xsd:<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#>
   SELECT ?subject ?model
    WHERE {?subject mtcars:wt "2.2"^^xsd:decimal .
           ?subject mtcars:model ?model .
          }'
# - send query to triplestore via rdf_query():
res <- rdf_query(triplestore,
                 query = sparqlQuery,
                 data.frame = T)
# - show result
print(res)

3.2 Find out a thing or two about Mazda RX4

# - Mazda RX4: id, model, and wt
sparqlQuery <-
  'PREFIX mtcars:<http://e-rum2020_example.com/mtcars#>  
   SELECT ?id ?model ?wt ?cyl ?disp
    WHERE {?id mtcars:wt ?wt .
           ?id mtcars:cyl ?cyl .
           ?id mtcars:disp ?disp .
           ?id mtcars:model "Mazda RX4" .
           ?id mtcars:model ?model .
          }'
res <- rdf_query(triplestore,
                 query = sparqlQuery,
                 data.frame = T)
print(res)

3.3 SELECT * FROM ...

How to SELECT * FROM ...: reconstruct the mtcars data.frame in triplestore representation:

sparqlQuery <-
  'SELECT ?subject ?predicate ?object 
    WHERE {?subject ?predicate ?object .}'
res <- rdf_query(triplestore,
                 query = sparqlQuery,
                 data.frame = T)
print(res)

3.4 All Fiat, Mazda, or Merceds cars, w. mpg and cyl:

# - all Fiat, Mazda, or Merceds cars, w. mpg and cyl
sparqlQuery <-
  'PREFIX mtcars:<http://e-rum2020_example.com/mtcars#> 
   SELECT ?id ?model ?mpg ?cyl
    WHERE {?id mtcars:model ?model .
           ?id mtcars:mpg ?mpg .
           ?id mtcars:cyl ?cyl .
           FILTER regex (?model, "Fiat|Mazda|Merc") .
          }'

res <- rdf_query(triplestore,
                 query = sparqlQuery,
                 data.frame = T)
print(res)

3.4 mtcars becomes a data.frame again

Finally, a complete reconstruction of mtcars:

# - all Fiat, Mazda, or Merceds cars, w. mpg and cyl
sparqlQuery <-
  'PREFIX mtcars:<http://e-rum2020_example.com/mtcars#> 
   SELECT ?model ?mpg ?cyl ?disp ?hp ?drat ?wt ?qsec ?vs ?am ?gear ?carb 
    WHERE {?id mtcars:model ?model;
              mtcars:mpg ?mpg;
              mtcars:cyl ?cyl;
              mtcars:disp ?disp;
              mtcars:hp ?hp;
              mtcars:drat ?drat;
              mtcars:wt ?wt;
              mtcars:qsec ?qsec;
              mtcars:vs ?vs;
              mtcars:am ?am;
              mtcars:gear ?gear;
              mtcars:carb ?carb .
    }'

res <- rdf_query(triplestore,
                 query = sparqlQuery,
                 data.frame = T)
print(res)
# - clean up (!)
rdf_free(triplestore)

4. Examples

4.1 When the datasets is delivered through a SPARQL end-point

Nice: rdf_parse will work with the Internet. In this particular example, the dataset on the Total revenues of the electronic communications sector from data.europa.eu is delivered in the following way: - the dataset webpage offers several formats, - but for the RDF/XML format it actually makes a SPARQL call to its end-point and delivers the result in the desired serialization from a query (see: the All available observations for the indicator, in RDF/XML format version of the dataset and hover mouse pointer over the DOWNLOAD button); - see eu_telecom_query.txt in the _code directory of this repo to find out that I have stored the query there (note: URL encoded + parameters i.e. format=application:rdf+xml).

options(rdf_print_format = 'ntriples',

rdf_parse(
  doc = queryRDF,
  format = "rdfxml",
  rdf = rdf_web

4.2 DBpedia through {SPARQL}

The {SPARQL} package is useful in interaction with SPARQL endpoints. It exposes one function, SPARQL:SPARQL() to connect to an endpoint, and has a built-in vector of common namespaces and their prefixes:

print(SPARQL::commonns)

SPARQL:SPARQL() returns a nicely formatted data.frame populated by the values of query variables. Let’s use {SPARQL} to connect to DBpedia: fetch Italian cities with more than 10,000 inhabitants and their names in Italian.

dbpedia_endpoint <- 'http://dbpedia.org/sparql'
sparqlQuery <-"prefix dbpedia: <http://dbpedia.org/resource/>
               prefix dbpedia-owl: <http://dbpedia.org/ontology/> 
               SELECT DISTINCT ?cityURI ?city ?population ?latitude ?longitude
                 WHERE {
                   ?cityURI dbpedia-owl:country dbpedia:Italy .
                   ?cityURI geo:lat  ?latitude .
                   ?cityURI geo:long  ?longitude .
                   ?cityURI rdfs:label ?city .
                   ?cityURI dbpedia-owl:populationTotal ?population .
                   FILTER (lang(?city) = 'it') .
                   FILTER (?population > 10000) .
                 }"
res <- SPARQL(url = dbpedia_endpoint,
              query = sparqlQuery)
print(str(res))
